We know that the rationals are countable since we can list them via zig-zagging: $$ egin{matrix}  rac{1}{1}   &&  rac{1}{2} &\color{red}	o & rac{1}{3} && rac{1}{4} & \color{red}	o &  rac{1}{5}\ \color{red}\downarrow   & \color{red}
earrow && \color{red}\swarrow && \color{red}
earrow &&\color{red}\swarrow\  rac{2}{1}   &&  rac{2}{2} &&  rac{2}{3} \ & \color{red}\swarrow && \color{red}
earrow\  rac{3}{1}&& rac{3}{2}&&& \ddots\ \color{red}\downarrow&\color{red}
earrow\  rac{4}{1} \end{matrix}$$ Now suppose we have a function $f: \mathbb N^2 	o A$ for some set $A$, where we list the outputs of the function in the same way: $$ egin{matrix} f(1,1) && f(1,2) && f(1,3)  && f(1,4) && f(1,5)\ ~\ f(2,1) && f(2,2) && f(2,3) \ ~\ f(3,1) && f(3,2) &&& \ddots\ ~\ f(4,1) \end{matrix}$$ Is there a way to define a function $f' : \mathbb N 	o A$ such the resulting sequence of outputs travels along this grid in the same way? $$ egin{matrix} f(1,1)   && f(1,2) &\color{red}	o &f(1,3) &&f(1,4)& \color{red}	o & f(1,5)\ \color{red}\downarrow   & \color{red}
earrow && \color{red}\swarrow && \color{red}
earrow &&\color{red}\swarrow\ f(2,1)   && f(2,2) && f(2,3) \ & \color{red}\swarrow && \color{red}
earrow\ f(3,1) && f(3,2) &&& \ddots\ \color{red}\downarrow&\color{red}
earrow\ f(4,1) \end{matrix}$$ That is, defining $f'$ in terms of $f$ such that $$ f'(1) = f(1,1)\ f'(2) = f(2,1) \ f'(3) = f(1,2) \ f'(4) = f(1,3) \ f'(5) = f(2,2) \ f'(6) = f(3,1) \  \vdots$$ Given $n\in\mathbb N$ I need to find a way to map to the corresponding pair in $\mathbb N^2$, expressing this only in terms of $n$, but I'm not sure how to do this. I appreciate any assistance.

